# spawriter MCP Tools

You have access to **spawriter** MCP tools that control the user's real Chrome tab via CDP (Chrome DevTools Protocol). This is NOT a headless browser — all actions affect the user's visible browser.

**You should proactively use these tools whenever browser context would improve your work.** Do not wait for the user to explicitly ask you to look at the page — if seeing the page would help you give a better answer or verify your work, just do it. Especially when you are given an URL. 

## Available Tools (30)

### Inspection & State

| Tool | Description | Key Args |
|------|-------------|----------|
| `dashboard_state` | Get single-spa app list, statuses, active import-map-overrides | `appName?` |
| `screenshot` | Capture page screenshot, optionally with numbered labels on interactive elements | `labels?` (boolean) |
| `accessibility_snapshot` | Get condensed accessibility tree with search, diff, and interactive_only support. Returns @ref numbers on interactive elements. | `search?`, `diff?`, `interactive_only?` |
| `execute` | Run JS in page context (fast, lightweight, direct CDP) | `code` |
| `playwright_execute` | Run code in Node.js VM sandbox with full Playwright API — supports click, hover, fill, drag, keyboard, scroll, tap, wait, and all locator strategies. All actions trigger real browser input events (CSS :hover/:focus work correctly) | `code`, `timeout?` |
| `interact` | Interact with a page element by @ref number from accessibility_snapshot. Lightweight alternative to playwright_execute for single-step actions (click, hover, fill, focus, check, uncheck, select). | `ref`, `action`, `value?` |
| `console_logs` | Get captured browser console logs with filtering | `count?`, `level?`, `search?`, `clear?` |
| `network_log` | Get captured network requests with filtering | `count?`, `url_filter?`, `status_filter?`, `clear?` |
| `network_detail` | Get full details of a specific request: headers, request/response body | `requestId`, `include?`, `max_body_size?` |
| `browser_fetch` | Make HTTP requests in the browser context with the user's cookies and session | `url`, `method?`, `headers?`, `body?`, `max_body_size?` |
| `trace` | Record user interactions on the page (clicks, typing, scrolling) | `action` (start/stop/status) |

